{"parse":{"title":"Angelo Nocchiero di Staglieno (sculpture)","pageid":53701125,"revid":805910004,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-Orphan\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"display: none\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Wiki letter w.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/60px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/80px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"44\" data-file-height=\"44\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>is an <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Orphan\" title=\"Wikipedia:Orphan\">orphan</a>, as no other articles <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere&amp;target=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;namespace=0\">link to it</a></b>. Please <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Link\" title=\"Help:Link\">introduce links</a> to this page from <span class=\"plainlinks\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special%3ASearch&amp;redirs=1&amp;search=Angelo+Nocchiero+di+Staglieno+%28sculpture%29&amp;fulltext=Search&amp;ns0=1&amp;title=Special%3ASearch&amp;advanced=1&amp;fulltext=Angelo+Nocchiero+di+Staglieno+%28sculpture%29\">related articles</a></span>; try the <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//edwardbetts.com/find_link?q=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)\">Find link tool</a> for suggestions.  <small><i>(October 2017)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>'<b>L'Angelo Nocchiero'</b> ('<b>The Angel-Helmsman'</b>) is a marble sculpture in the '<a href=\"/wiki/Symbolism_(arts)\" title=\"Symbolism (arts)\">symbolist</a>' style by the Genovese sculptor <a href=\"https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giovanni_Scanzi\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"it:Giovanni Scanzi\">Giovanni Scanzi</a> (1840-1915), completed in 1886. It was commissioned by <a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Tomba_Giacomo_Carpaneto_(Cimitero_di_Staglieno)\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"commons:Category:Tomba Giacomo Carpaneto (Cimitero di Staglieno)\">Giacomo Carpaneto</a>, Cav. Mauriziano (1811-1878) as a monument for his family tomb in the <a href=\"https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cimitero_monumentale_di_Staglieno\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"it:Cimitero monumentale di Staglieno\">Cimitero monumentale di Staglieno</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Monumental_Cemetery_of_Staglieno\" title=\"Monumental Cemetery of Staglieno\">Monumental Cemetery of Staglieno</a>), in <a href=\"/wiki/Genoa\" title=\"Genoa\">Genova, Italy</a>.\nAlong with the sculpture for the <a href=\"/wiki/Monteverde_Angel\" title=\"Monteverde Angel\">Oneto Family</a> sculpted by Giulio Monteverde in 1882,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> the Carpaneto monument has become one of the most recognisable icons of Staglieno,\nappearing on an official cemetery brochure in 2014.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg/220px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"323\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg/330px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg/440px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2540\" data-file-height=\"3728\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_11_vintage.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Angelo Nocchiero</i> (1886), Giovanni Scanzi, sculptor (early photograph, ca.1895)</div></div></div>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#The_Artist,_His_Patron_and_His_Model\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The Artist, His Patron and His Model</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Symbolism\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Symbolism</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Restoration\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Restoration</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Gallery\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Gallery</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-8\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">8</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-9\"><a href=\"#Bibliography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">9</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bibliography</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span id=\"The_Artist.2C_His_Patron_and_His_Model\"></span><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_Artist,_His_Patron_and_His_Model\">The Artist, His Patron and His Model</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: The Artist, His Patron and His Model\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Giovanni Scanzi was 38 years old when his patron Cav. Giacomo Carpaneto died and he began\nwork on the Carpaneto family tomb at Staglieno. Scanzi's early work was in the Realist style,\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sborgi_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sborgi-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\nand by this time he had also incorporated Symbolism\n(or, perhaps more accurately, \"l'iperdecorativismo eclettico\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sborgi_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sborgi-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>),\nas seen in his sculptures of the\n<i>Angelo della Resurrezione</i> (Angel of Resurrection) on the Carlo di G.B. Casella family tomb (1877);\nthe later relief for the tomb of Elisa Falcone (1893); and other works at Staglieno.\n</p><p>Giacomo Carpaneto, Cav. Mauriziano (1811-1878) was a respected merchant,\npart of a family originally from\nSampierdarena (S. Petri ad Arenaria) where the Palazzo Centurione-Carpaneto still\nstands.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Marchetti_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Marchetti-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\nSignora Carpaneto also is interred in the family tomb.\n</p><p>The model for the <i>Angelo Nocchiero</i> sculpture was Antonio Dellapiane (1868-1942).\nAfter school, he worked as a shop-boy in a joiner's workshop in Sampierdarena, where Scanzi\nmet him. Later, he started his own workshop, becoming a successful carpenter and wood carver.\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-Marchetti_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Marchetti-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Symbolism\">Symbolism</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Symbolism\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The sculpture depicts an angel, standing astride a small boat, beginning to secure the sails\nat the end of a journey. His garments are streaming behind him, suggesting a strong wind.\nThe prow of the boat is the stoic face of a woman, and under the prow the water swirls.\nRopes are coiled in minute detail inside the boat (even though the average cemetery visitor\nwould not be able to see them), and at the back of the boat is an embroidered cushion, slightly\ndented from a head resting there until a moment earlier.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The boat would be a familiar symbol to anyone in 19th century Genova, a seaport town,\nand the <i>Angelo Nocchiero</i> - <i>Angel Helmsman</i> - reminds the viewer of the spiritual\nboatmen of ancient mythology, whose job it was to transport the departed into the afterlife.\nThe clear imagery of the Guiding Angel is underscored by the epigraph in bronze lettering\non the pedestal: \"AVVENTURATO CHI NEL MARE DELLA VITA EBBE NOCCHIERO S\u00cc FIDO\" - \"Blessed\nis he who on the sea of life had so sure a guide\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Many famous people of the 19th century visited Staglieno, including Friedrich Nietzsche,\nGuy de Maupassant, and Mark Twain, who wrote\nabout it in glowing terms in his <i>Innocents Abroad</i> (1868).\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\nThe visit in March 1893 of Empress Elisabeth of Austria, fondly known as 'Sissi', is legendary.\nPeriodicals of the time reported that she arrived incognito as 'Lady Parker', and walked\nfrom the Principe to Staglieno, visiting a number of significant places along the way.\nWhen she came before Scanzi's <i>Nocchiero</i>, she paused,<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> apparently moved, and after a period\nof contemplation, had the epigraph copied into her personal notebook.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Restoration\">Restoration</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Restoration\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg/220px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"367\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg/330px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg/440px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"990\" data-file-height=\"1650\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_00_during_restoration_angel_with_foam_1.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Angelo Nocchiero</i> (1886), during the 2016 restoration process</div></div></div>\n<p>Mark Twain <sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> described \nthe monuments at Staglieno as \"exquisitely wrought . . . full of grace and beauty.\nThey are new, and snowy; every outline is perfect.\" After a century and a half, of course,\nTwain's description would not be quite the same, as the dust, mildew and pollution of an\nindustrial city have settled on the marble surfaces, thieves have removed valuable bronze\nand other materials, and vandals have broken or otherwise defaced some of the monuments.\n<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Through the work of local restoration experts and societies and individuals dedicated to\nthe preservation of \"the largest outdoor sculpture museum in Europe\",<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Scanzi's <i>Angelo Nocchiero</i> underwent a complete restoration in 2016.\nBeginning with a \"spolveratura\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> - the removal of dust to allow a complete assessment of the\nrestoration work necessary - local experts worked for several months to remove the effects of time\nand abuse.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> The result can be seen in the Gallery on this page.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Gallery\">Gallery</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Angelo_Nocchiero_di_Staglieno_(sculpture)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Gallery\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional center\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto,_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi,_1886.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg/82px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg\" width=\"82\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg/123px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg/164px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi%2C_1886.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2377\" data-file-height=\"3485\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>L'Angelo Nocchiero</i> in 2010, before restoration\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto,_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg/90px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg/135px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg/180px-Tomba_Giacomo_Carpanetto%2C_opera_di_Giovanni_Scanzi.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3456\" data-file-height=\"4608\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>L'Angelo Nocchiero</i> in 2014, before restoration (monochrome image)\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg/80px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg\" width=\"80\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg/119px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg/159px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_03.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3538\" data-file-height=\"5326\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><i>L'Angelo Nocchiero</i> in 2017, after restoration (full view of niche)\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_04.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_04.jpg/80px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_04.jpg\" width=\"80\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_04.jpg/120px-Angelo_nocchiero_staglieno_04.jpg 1.5x, //uplo